Economics of Higher Ed - The Costs (4/15)
<p><img alt="Undergraduate Student Budget 18-19" src="https://libapps.s3.amazonaws.com/accounts/150004/images/udergraduate_budget.png" style="width: 960px; height: 398px;" /></p>

<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Graph source: <a href="https://trends.collegeboard.org/college-pricing/figures-tables/published-prices-national#Student%20Budgets,%202018-19" target="_blank">College Board &quot;Published Prices--National&quot;</a></strong></p>

<p><span style="font-size:16px;">The published price of tuition, fees, room and board, as well as books and supplies is often referred to as the &quot;sticker price&quot; for the school. Students who do not receive financial aid will pay the full sticker price to attend the college.&nbsp;</span></p>

<p><span style="font-size:16px;">The average &quot;sticker price&quot; for an institution is for one year of attendance. The total price for a degree will depend on how long a student takes to graduate. In a <a href="https://nces.ed.gov/programs/coe/indicator_ctr.asp" target="_blank">2018 report on undergraduate retention and graduation rates from the National Center for Education Statistics</a>, &quot;60 percent of students who began seeking a Bachelor&#39;s degree at a 4-year institution in fall 2010 completed that degree within 6 years&quot;.&nbsp;</span></p>

<p><span style="font-size:16px;">From a <a href="http://nscresearchcenter.org/signaturereport9/#Introduction" target="_blank">report by the National Student Clearinghouse Research Center</a>, students who take 6 years to graduate spend 40% more than those who graduate in 4 years.&nbsp;</span></p>

Economics of Higher Ed - What can we Control? (5/15)
<p>Students face a mountain of expenses and responsibilities in order to succeed in college.The <a href="https://bigfuture.collegeboard.org/pay-for-college/college-costs/college-costs-faqs" target="_blank">College Board</a>&nbsp;insists that college is not as expensive as one may think as long as research and consideration is done when choosing a college.&nbsp;</p>

<p>In preparation for college, students must prepare to set aside money or request financial aid for:&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Tuition and Fees</strong> - This fee may change depending on credit hours taken, in-state and out-of-state status, and the type of institution the student is attending.&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Room and Board</strong> - Students may be charged for room and board when they choose to live on campus and can be considered an expense to anticipate. However, for commuter students, they must prepare to spend money on their own rent and living costs when they live off campus.&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Books and Supplies</strong> - The College Board anticipates students average about $1,300 for books for a full academic year for students at a four-year university. Colleges like James Madison University and Richard Bland College anticipate costs for books below the College Board Average while colleges like Virginia Commonwealth University and The College of William &amp; Mary anticipate costs for books above the average.&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Personal Expenses</strong> - Students must choose between maintaining their standard of living or altering it to fit within their college budget. Laundry, cell phone bills, food and entertainment are&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Transportation</strong> - No matter if they live on campus or off-campus, transportation is necessary for trips around the campus or home for the occasional visit. Students must be prepared to budget not only for gas, but potentially parking as well.&nbsp;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

Economics of the Textbook Industry - Introduction (6/15)
<p>In 2015&nbsp;this was the headline at NBC News:</p>

<h3><a href="https://www.nbcnews.com/feature/freshman-year/college-textbook-prices-have-risen-812-percent-1978-n399926" target="_blank"><strong>College Textbook Prices Have Risen 1,041 Percent Since 1977</strong></a></h3>

<p>&quot;According to NBC&#39;s review of Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS) data, textbook prices have risen over three times the rate of inflation from January 1977 to June 2015, a 1,041 percent increase.&quot;</p>

<p><iframe allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/De1261aMknQ" width="560"></iframe></p>

Economics of the Textbook Industry - Traditional Publishing Model (7/15)
<h3>Traditional Publishing Model</h3>

<p>In a traditional textbook publishing model, the publisher typically:</p>

<ul>
	<li>funds the textbook creation and production upfront&nbsp;and</li>
	<li>recoups costs and collects profits through sales</li>
</ul>

<p>The author typically:</p>

<ul>
	<li>is paid through royalties from sales and</li>
	<li>signs copyright over to publisher</li>
</ul>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><iframe allow="autoplay; fullscreen" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0" height="378" src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/333112415" width="640"></iframe></p>

<p><em>The graphics and information in this slide were&nbsp;created by Dave Ernst, licensed with a <u><a href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/">Creative Commons license </a></u>and adapted by Liz Thompson.</em></p>

Economics of the Textbook Industry - Alternative Publishing Model (8/15)
<h3>Alternative Publishing Model</h3>

<p>In an alternative publishing model, funding&nbsp;comes from a grant. The grantor typically:</p>

<ul>
	<li>funds the textbook creation and production upfront and</li>
	<li>requires an open license for publication</li>
</ul>

<p>The publisher typically:</p>

<ul>
	<li>is paid for services through the grant</li>
</ul>

<p>The author typically:</p>

<ul>
	<li>is paid for services&nbsp;through the grant and</li>
	<li>retains copyright under an open license</li>
</ul>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><iframe allow="autoplay; fullscreen" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0" height="378" src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/333118944" width="640"></iframe></p>

<h3>Where does&nbsp;funding come from? Grants often come from:</h3>

<ul>
	<li>Universities: <a href="https://textbooks.opensuny.org/nysoer/" target="_blank">SUNY</a>, <a href="https://www.library.umass.edu/oer/open-education-initiative/" target="_blank">UMass Amherst</a>, <a href="https://library.pdx.edu/services/pdxscholar-services/open-access-textbooks/" target="_blank">Portland State University</a>, and others</li>
	<li>Foundations: <a href="https://hewlett.org/strategy/open-educational-resources/" target="_blank">William and Flora Hewlett Foundation</a>&nbsp;and others</li>
	<li>Governments: at the state and federal levels (examples: <a href="https://vivalib.org/c.php?g=836990&amp;p=6425615" target="_blank">VIVA course redesign grant</a>&nbsp;and <a href="https://sparcopen.org/our-work/open-textbooks-fy19/" target="_blank">Federal Open textbook Pilot</a>)</li>
</ul>

Economics of the Textbook Industry - Open Licenses (9/15)
<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px;"><a href="http://indstudy1.org/univ/355460515034/Flash/Lesson2/PracticeVersion.html" target="_blank">Want to test your CC-license knowledge? Play this game! (Flash required)</a></span></p>

<p style="text-align: center;"><iframe allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/_Q3sbk7Zi1Q" width="560"></iframe></p>

<p><span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Attribution - CC BY:</strong> The license allows you to remix, reuse, retain, revise, and redistribute as long as you credit the original creation. </span></p>

<p><span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Attribution ShareAlike - CC BY-SA:</strong> This license allows you to remix and adapt upon the original work even for commercial purposes as long as you credit the original work and share your own work under an identical license. </span></p>

<p><span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Attribution NoDerivs - CC BY-ND: </strong>This license allows for redistribution, both commercial and non-commercial, as long as the work is whole and unchanged and credit is given to the original work. </span></p>

<p><span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Attribution NonCommercial - CC BY-NC: </strong>This license lets you remix, revise, and reuse the work non-commercially. Your changes must also be non-commercial and credit given to the original work. </span></p>

<p><span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Attribution NonCommercial ShareAlike - CC BY-NC-SA:</strong> This license lets you remix, revise, and reuse the original work non-commercially as long as you credit the original work and share your work under an identical license. </span></p>

<p><span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Attribution NonCommercial NoDerivs - CC BY-NC-ND: </strong>This license is the most restrictive and only allows you to share the original work non-commercially. You cannot change the work in any way.</span></p>

<p style="text-align: center;"><img alt="Creative Commons Licenses Images" src="https://libapps.s3.amazonaws.com/accounts/150004/images/creative-commons-licenses.png" style="width: 500px; height: 277px;" /></p>

