OER Efficacy - The Students (13/15)
<p style="text-align: center;"><iframe allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/od2O5aovYXo" width="560"></iframe></p>

<hr />
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Bliss, T., Hilton, J., Wiley, D., &amp; Thanos, K. (2013). The cost and quality of open textbooks: Perceptions of community college faculty and students. First Monday (18)1. Retrieved from https://journals.uic.edu/ojs/index.php/fm/article/view/3972/3383</strong></p>

<p>Eight community colleges primarily serving at-risk students collaborated together on Project Kaleidoscope. Project Kaleidoscope is focused on the adoption of OER in the institution. Project Kaleidoscope affected 2,000 students divided among 40 teachers. A questionnaire was sent to faculty for students&#39; preparedness, experience teaching the course with the OER, and the perception of use compared to the previous texts. Students were also sent a questionnaire to identify typical amount of spending on textbooks, perception of OER quality, and likelihood of registering for other courses that use OER. 11 instructors responded to the survey and 132 students responded.&nbsp;</p>

<p>Instructors reported that there is a somewhat initial hidden cost to the adoption of an OER as they must adjust teaching style and strategy. 70 percent of instructors indicated that students used their OER textbook at least two-to-three times a week and 90 percent of instructors reported that students were equally prepared (60 percent) or more prepared (30 percent). All 11 instructors who responded said they would be very likely to use open texts in future courses.&nbsp;</p>

<p>64 percent of students reported using the OER textbook at least two-to-three times per week. 56 percent of students said the quality of the text was the same quality of texts in other courses and 41 percent stated the OER was better than the quality of texts in other courses. 77 percent reported they would be very likely or somewhat likely to register for a futrue course with online texts. 75 percent of students considered the OER text as being a positive experience.&nbsp;</p>

<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Feldstein, A., Marin, M., Hudson, A., Warren, Kiara, Hilton, J., Wiley, D. (2012). Open textbooks and increased student access and outcomes. European Journal of Open, Distance, and e-Learning 2. Retrieved from https://eric.ed.gov/?id=EJ992490&nbsp;</strong></p>

<p>The School of Business at Virginia State University (VSU) began to explore ways to improve the student experience around the course content. VSU identified Flat World Knowledge, a publisher of open textbooks, and partnered with them to give students in the business school access to the open textbook while also paying a fee to give students access to flash cards, quizzes, and videos for studying. The textbook was provided to students in PDF, Kindle reader, MP3, and other electronic formats. Students who registered for a Flat World Knowledge license were invited to take a survey at the end of every semester. Over 90 percent of respondents considered the textbook easy to both use and read. About 70 percent of students agreed that the portability of the Flat World Knowledge digital content was more preferable to traditional textbooks.&nbsp;</p>

<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Vojtech, G. &amp; Grissett, J. (2017). Student perceptions of college faculty who use OER. International Review of Research in Open and Distributed Learning (18)4. Retrieved from http://www.irrodl.org/index.php/irrodl/article/view/3032/4215</strong></p>

<p>At a small public college, 23 students from two upper-level psychology courses were asked to read two passages about a fictional &quot;Dr. Wilson&quot;. In one passage, Dr. Wilson used a traditional textbook and in another passage Dr. Wilson used an open textbook and they were rated on many characteristics: kindness, knowledgeability, enthusiasm, patience, encouragement, and creativity. Students were also requested to provided justification for their responses. Students justified an open, or cheaper, textbook alternative as being the reason they rated &quot;Dr. Wilson&quot; as being kinder and more creative--with students also using this justification for signing up for more classes with the professor that provided the open alternative. Although there were responses that stated that the passage did not adequately support &quot;Dr. Wilson&#39;s&quot; kindness and patience, there is a mental justification among the small population that low-cost alternatives provided by the professor made them nicer and more supportive.&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="text-align: center;">Optional video: Santa Ana College OER Student Panel from&nbsp;</span>OpenEd<span style="text-align: center;">&nbsp;2017</span></p>

<p style="text-align: center;"><iframe allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/vtPm3zsSfWo" width="560"></iframe></p>

OER Efficacy - The Numbers (14/15)
<p style="text-align: center;"><iframe allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/SX0K0hb_xKE" width="560"></iframe></p>

<hr />
<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Allen, G., Guzman-Alvarez, A., Molinaro, M., &amp; Larsen, D.S. (2015). Assessing the impact and efficacy of the Open-Access ChemWiki Textbook Project. EDUCase. Retrieved from&nbsp;<a href="https://library.educause.edu/-/media/files/library/2015/1/elib1501-pdf.pdf">https://library.educause.edu/-/media/files/library/2015/1/elib1501-pdf.pdf</a></strong></span></p>

<p><span style="font-size:16px;">The ChemWiki is an open resource from the Hyperlibrary project. The Hyperlibrary was initiated by the University of California, Davis to reduce the growing educational cost of STEM fields. The ChemWiki was evaluated in a pilot of two classes that used the Wiki and one class that used the commercial textbook. A survey was given to all students to identify online versus textbook access and their opinions. Grades and study performance was also evaluated. Results showed that classes that both performed equally well and had the same normalized learning gains. While this may show that OER do not improve the grades or study habits of the student, it does demonstrate that students perform equally well compared to their cohorts using the traditional textbook.&nbsp;</span></p>

<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Grewe, K.E. &amp; Davis, W.P. (2017). The impact of enrollment in an OER course on student learning outcomes. International Review of Research in Open and Distributed Learning (18)4, 231-238. Retrieved from&nbsp;<a href="http://www.irrodl.org/index.php/irrodl/article/view/2986/4209" target="_blank">http://www.irrodl.org/index.php/irrodl/article/view/2986/4209</a></strong></span></p>

<p><span style="font-size:16px;">In a study from Northern Virginia Community College system, 146 students were enrolled in an 8-week&nbsp;section of a history class. Three sections utilized OER and three did not. There was a moderate positive correlation between OER versus non-OER and student achievement. This result shows that there is a moderately positive relationship between taking an OER course and academic achievement.</span></p>

<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Pawlyshyn, N., Braddlee, Casper, L,, Miller, H. (2013). Adopting OER: A case study of cross-institutional collaboration and innovation. EDUCASE. Retrieved from&nbsp;<a href="https://er.educause.edu/articles/2013/11/adopting-oer-a-case-study-of-crossinstitutional-collaboration-and-innovation">https://er.educause.edu/articles/2013/11/adopting-oer-a-case-study-of-crossinstitutional-collaboration-and-innovation</a>&nbsp;</strong></span></p>

<p><span style="font-size:16px;">At Mercy College, The Project Kaleidoscope Open Course Initiative (KOCI) was initiated to target critical reading and math competencies in collaboration with other institutions. Course modules and outlines were created with faculty teaching classes to a total of 600 students. Mercy faculty reported nearly 10 percent reduction in course failures in the first semester of using KOCI. Success rates for reading and persistence increased in sections in which KOCI was used. Algebra courses dropped their previously used licenses and costly math books and resources, saving students a total of $125,000 in the first year. At the end of the pilot, Mercy&#39;s Math Department announced that all sections in basic mathematics would use KOCI.&nbsp;</span></p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

OER Efficacy - The Bibliography (15/15)
<p>The following list of research articles explore the efficacy and quality of student learning using open textbooks. The studies span disciplines, institution types, and student academic level.</p>

<h3><strong>Efficacy studies:</strong></h3>

<p><em>Across 13 academic studies that attempted to measure results pertaining to student learning (higher ed: 15,784 treatment, 99,692 control, k12: 1,805 treatment 2,439 control) none showed results in which students who utilized OER performed worse than their peers who used traditional textbooks.</em></p>

<p style="margin-left:.5in;"><a href="http://www.educause.edu/library/resources/assessing-impact-and-efficacy-open-access-chemwiki-textbook-project">Allen, G., Guzman-Alvarez, A., Molinaro, M., Larsen, D. (2015)</a>. Assessing the Impact and Efficacy of the Open-Access ChemWiki Textbook Project. Educause Learning Initiative Brief, January 2015. See also <a href="http://chemwiki.ucdavis.edu/@api/deki/files/33530/Newsletter.10.pdf">this newsletter</a>.</p>

<p style="margin-left:.5in;"><a href="http://www.sr.ithaka.org/publications/interactive-learning-online-at-public-universities-evidence-from-randomized-trials/">Bowen, W. G., Chingos, M. M., Lack, K. A., &amp; Nygren, T. I. (2012)</a>. <em>Interactive Learning Online at Public Universities: Evidence from Randomized Trials</em>. Ithaka S+R.</p>

<p style="margin-left:.5in;"><a href="http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/pam.21728/full">Bowen, W. G., Chingos, M. M., Lack, K. A., &amp; Nygren, T. I. (2014)</a>. Interactive Learning Online at Public Universities: Evidence from a Six‐Campus Randomized Trial. <em>Journal of Policy Analysis and Management</em>, <em>33</em>(1), 94-111.</p>

<p style="margin-left:.5in;"><a href="http://www.eurodl.org/index.php?p=archives&amp;year=2012&amp;halfyear=2&amp;article=533">Feldstein, A., Martin, M., Hudson, A., Warren, K., Hilton, J., &amp; Wiley, D. (2012)</a>. Open textbooks and increased student access and outcomes. <em>European Journal of Open, Distance and E-Learning</em>. Retrieved from <a href="http://www.eurodl.org/index.php?p=archives&amp;year=2012&amp;halfyear=2&amp;article=533">http://www.eurodl.org/index.php?p=archives&amp;year=2012&amp;halfyear=2&amp;article=533</a>.</p>

<p style="margin-left:.5in;"><a href="http://www.ijee.ie/contents/c290613.html">Gil, P., Candelas, F., Jara, C., Garcia, G., Torres, F (2013)</a>. Web-based OERs in Computer Networks.&nbsp;<em>International Journal of Engineering Education</em>, 29(6), 1537-1550. (OA&nbsp;<a href="http://openedgroup.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Manuscript_draft_ijee2802ns.pdf">preprint</a>)</p>

<p style="margin-left:.5in;"><a href="http://www.irrodl.org/index.php/irrodl/article/view/1523/2652">Hilton, J., Gaudet, D., Clark, P., Robinson, J., &amp; Wiley, D. (2013).</a> The adoption of open educational resources by one community college math department. <em>The International Review of Research in Open and Distance Learning</em>, <em>14</em>(4), 37&ndash;50.</p>

<p style="margin-left:.5in;"><u>Hilton, J., &amp; Laman, C. (2012)</u>. One college&rsquo;s use of an open psychology textbook. <em>Open Learning: The Journal of Open and Distance Learning</em>, <em>27</em>(3), 201&ndash;217. Retrieved from <a href="http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/02680513.2012.716657">http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/02680513.2012.716657</a>.</p>

<p style="margin-left:.5in;"><a href="https://oli.cmu.edu/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/Lovett_2008_Statistics_Accelerated_Learning_Study.pdf">Lovett, M., Meyer, O., &amp; Thille, C. (2008)</a>. The open learning initiative: Measuring the effectiveness of the OLI statistics course in accelerating student learning.&nbsp;<em>Journal of Interactive Media in Education</em>,&nbsp;<em>2008 </em>(1).</p>

<p style="margin-left:.5in;"><a href="http://er.educause.edu/articles/2013/11/adopting-oer-a-case-study-of-crossinstitutional-collaboration-and-innovation">Pawlyshyn, Braddlee, Casper and Miller (2013).</a> Adopting OER: A Case Study of Cross-Institutional Collaboration and Innovation. <em>Educause Review</em>. &nbsp;Robinson, T.J. (2015). <em>Open Textbooks: The Effects of Open Educational Resource Adoption on Measures of Post-secondary Student Success</em> (Doctoral dissertation). &nbsp;</p>

<p style="margin-left:.5in;"><a href="http://edr.sagepub.com/content/43/7/341.full">Robinson T. J., Fischer, L., Wiley, D. A., &amp; Hilton, J. (2014)</a>. The impact of open textbooks on secondary science learning outcomes. <em>Educational Researcher</em>, 43(7): 341-351.</p>

<p style="margin-left:.5in;"><a href="http://www.irrodl.org/index.php/irrodl/article/view/1153/2256">Wiley, D., Hilton, J. Ellington, S., and Hall, T. (2012)</a>. &ldquo;A preliminary examination of the cost savings and learning impacts of using open textbooks in middle and high school science classes.&rdquo; <em>International Review of Research in Open and Distance Learning</em>. 13 (3), pp. 261-276.</p>

<h3><strong>Quality studies:</strong></h3>

<p><em>In terms of student and teacher perceptions of OER, 2,717 students and 2,484 faculty members were surveyed across&nbsp;nine peer-reviewed studies. Approximately 50% said that the OER resources were as good as traditional resources, 35% said the OER were superior and 15% said they were inferior.</em></p>

<p style="margin-left:.5in;"><a href="http://www.onlinelearningsurvey.com/oer.html">Allen, I., Seaman, J. (2014)</a>. Opening the Curriculum: Open Educational Resources in U.S. Higher Education, 2014.</p>

<p style="margin-left:.5in;"><a href="http://jime.open.ac.uk/article/download/2013-04/478">Bliss, T., Robinson, T. J., Hilton, J., &amp; Wiley, D. (2013)</a>. An OER COUP: College teacher and student perceptions of Open Educational Resources. <em>Journal of Interactive Media in Education</em>, 1&ndash;25.</p>

<p style="margin-left:.5in;"><a href="http://firstmonday.org/ojs/index.php/fm/article/view/3972/3383">Bliss, T., Hilton, J., Wiley, D., Thanos, K. (2013).</a> The cost and quality of open textbooks: Perceptions of community college faculty and students. <em>First Monday</em>, 18:1.</p>

<p style="margin-left:.5in;"><a href="http://www.eurodl.org/index.php?p=archives&amp;year=2012&amp;halfyear=2&amp;article=533">Feldstein, A., Martin, M., Hudson, A., Warren, K., Hilton, J., &amp; Wiley, D. (2012)</a>. Open textbooks and increased student access and outcomes. <em>European Journal of Open, Distance and E-Learning</em>. Retrieved from <a href="http://www.eurodl.org/index.php?p=archives&amp;year=2012&amp;halfyear=2&amp;article=533">http://www.eurodl.org/index.php?p=archives&amp;year=2012&amp;halfyear=2&amp;article=533</a>.</p>

